Right, that still makes sense.
{% endsc %}</p><blockquote><p>If <a href="https://nodejs.org/docs/latest-v15.x/api/http.html#http_response_writehead_statuscode_statusmessage_headers"><code>response.writeHead()</code></a> method is called and this method has not been called, it will directly write the supplied header values onto the network channel without caching internally, and the <a href="https://nodejs.org/docs/latest-v15.x/api/http.html#http_response_getheader_name"><code>response.getHeader()</code></a> on the header will not yield the expected result. If progressive population of headers is desired with potential future retrieval and modification, use <a href="https://nodejs.org/docs/latest-v15.x/api/http.html#http_response_setheader_name_value"><code>response.setHeader()</code></a> instead of <a href="https://nodejs.org/docs/latest-v15.x/api/http.html#http_response_writehead_statuscode_statusmessage_headers"><code>response.writeHead()</code></a>.</p></blockquote><p>{% sc bearsays %}
